'''Marc Cucurella Saseta''' ({{IPA|ca|ˈmaɾ(k) kukuˈɾeʎə səˈzɛtə}}; born 22 July 1998) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left-back]] or [[left wing-back]] for {{English football updater|Chelsea}} club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]]. He is considered one of the best left-backs in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/ranked-best-left-backs-in-the-world|title=Ranked! The 10 best left-backs in the world|publisher=[[FourFourTwo]]|first=Mark|last=White|date=16 June 2025|access-date=18 December 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/the-best-left-backs-in-world-soccer-ranked|title=The 25 Best Left Backs in World Soccer — Ranked|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=14 July 2025|access-date=18 December 2025}}</ref>

Cucurella made his senior club debut at [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], but spent most of his time there with the [[FC Barcelona B|reserve team]]. He went on to play over 100 [[La Liga]] games for [[SD Eibar|Eibar]] and [[Getafe CF|Getafe]], before joining [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in 2021. He spent a season with Brighton before joining Chelsea in 2022, winning the [[UEFA Conference League|Conference League]] and the [[FIFA Club World Cup]] three years later.

Cucurella was [[Cap (association football)|capped]] for Spain over every youth level from [[Spain national under-16 football team|under-16]] to [[Spain national under-23 football team|under-23]], winning the silver medal with the latter at the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Olympic tournament]]. He made his debut for the senior team in 2021 and later represented the side at [[UEFA Euro 2024]], where Spain won the tournament.

==Club career==
===Barcelona and Eibar===
Cucurella was born in [[Alella]], [[Province of Barcelona|Barcelona]], Catalonia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe369320/cucurella/ |title=Cucurella: Profile |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL |access-date=27 August 2022}}</ref> He started playing [[futsal]] with FS Alella before joining [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]]'s youth teams in 2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://futbolbasecatala.cat/es/barca/marc-cucurella-saseta:14-578 |title=Marc Cucurella Saseta |publisher=Futbol Base Català |language=ca |access-date=19 August 2017}}</ref> and in 2012, he moved to [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20131205/mundo-barsa/cantera/marc-cucurella-el-puyol-de-la-cantera_54393907174.html |title=Marc Cucurella, el Puyol de la cantera|trans-title=Marc Cucurella, the Puyol from the youth setup |newspaper=Mundo Deportivo |language=es |date=14 December 2013|access-date=19 August 2017}}</ref> On 26 November 2016, while still a junior, he made his senior debut with [[FC Barcelona B|the reserves]] by starting in a 4–0 home win over [[CE L'Hospitalet|L'Hospitalet]] in the [[Segunda División B]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/fc-barcelona/cantera/20161126/412189418772/barca-b-barcelona-filial-4-0-golea-hospitalet-lider.html |title=4–0: el Barça B golea al Hospitalet y sigue líder|trans-title=4–0: ''Barça'' B thrash Hospitalet and remain leader |newspaper=Mundo Deportivo |language=es |date=26 November 2016|access-date=19 August 2017}}</ref>

Cucurella contributed with 17 appearances for the side, [[2016–17 Segunda División B|achieving promotion]] to the [[Segunda División]] via [[2017 Segunda División B play-offs|the play-offs]]. On 7 July 2017, he renewed his contract until 2021, with a €12&nbsp;million clause.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/barcelona/story/3154580/marc-cucurella-signs-new-barcelona-deal-with-12-million-clause |title=Marc Cucurella signs new Barcelona deal with €12 million clause |website=ESPN FC |date=7 July 2017|access-date=19 August 2017}}</ref> He made his professional debut on 1 September, starting in a 2–2 away draw against [[Granada CF|Granada]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galicia |first1=Samuel |title=Tercer empate de un Granada que no termina de arrancar|trans-title=Third draw for a Granada that can't get going |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/2017/09/01/59a9c93eca4741702f8b45c8.html |access-date=8 May 2022 |newspaper=Marca|location=Spain |date=1 September 2017 |language=es}}</ref> He made his first-team debut on 24 October, coming on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Lucas Digne]] in a 3–0 [[Copa del Rey]] away win against [[Real Murcia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/barcelona/story/3242741/barcelona-b-teamer-jose-arnaiz-thrilled-with-goal-in-dream-first-team-debut |title=Barcelona B teamer Jose Arnaiz thrilled with goal in 'dream' first-team debut |website=ESPN FC |date=24 October 2017|access-date=25 October 2017}}</ref> He scored his first senior goal for Barcelona B on 17 March 2018, equalising in a draw away to [[Lorca FC|Lorca]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martínez |first1=Alfonso |title=Cucurella priva a Fabri de su primera alegría y salva al filial|trans-title=Cucurella deprives Fabri of his first joy and saves the reserves |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/2018/03/17/5aad5acbe2704e8d398b4587.html |access-date=8 May 2022 |newspaper=Marca|location=Spain |date=17 March 2018 |language=es}}</ref>

On 31 August 2018, Cucurella was [[Loan (association football)|loaned]] to fellow [[La Liga]] club [[SD Eibar]], for one year with a €2&nbsp;million buyout clause.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.cat/futbol/barca-b/noticies/2018-2019/acord-amb-la-sd-eibar-per-a-la-cessio-de-cucurella |title=Acord amb la SD Eibar per a la cessió de Cucurella|trans-title=Agreement with SD Eibar for the loan of Cucurella |publisher=FC Barcelona |language=ca |date=31 August 2018|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> He made his top-flight debut on 25 September in a 1–0 loss away to Espanyol. Appearing as one of eight changes by manager [[José Luis Mendilibar]], he was praised by ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' journalist Ander Barroso despite the result.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barroso |first1=Ander |title=Cucurella emerge con fuerza|trans-title=Cucurella emerges strongly |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/eibar/2018/09/27/5bad1813268e3e092f8b4594.html |access-date=8 May 2022 |newspaper=Marca|location=Spain |date=27 September 2018 |language=es}}</ref> He scored his first La Liga goal on the final day of the season on 9 May 2019, opening the scoring in 2–2 draw at home to his parent club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Title-winners Barcelona held to a draw in final league game at Eibar |url=https://jerseyeveningpost.com/uksport/2019/05/19/title-winners-barcelona-held-to-a-draw-in-final-league-game-at-eibar/ |access-date=8 May 2022 |newspaper=Jersey Evening Post |date=19 May 2019}}</ref>

===Getafe===
[[File:Marc Cucurella (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Cucurella playing for [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] in 2019]]
At the end of his loan, Eibar exercised Cucurella's clause, making him a permanent player for the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque]] team; along with the transfer, Barcelona added a €4&nbsp;million buyback option.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://as.com/futbol/2019/05/27/primera/1558958774_939539.html |title=El Eibar ejerce la claúsula de compra de Marc Cucurella|trans-title=Eibar triggers Marc Cucurella's buyout clause |newspaper=Diario AS |language=es |date=27 May 2019}}</ref> On 16 July 2019, after just sixteen days as a permanent Eibar player, this clause was activated,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/us/laliga/news/barcelona-buy-back-cucurella-from-eibar/1243811 |title=Barcelona Buy Back Cucurella From Eibar |publisher=beIN Sports |date=16 July 2019}}</ref> only for him to be loaned to [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] two days later for the upcoming season, with an option to buy for €6&nbsp;million and 40% of the rights remaining to Barcelona.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1288455/agreement-with-getafe-for-the-loan-of-marc-cucurella |title=Agreement with Getafe for the loan of Marc Cucurella |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=18 July 2019|access-date=18 July 2019}}</ref>

Cucurella made his European debut on 19 September 2019 as a substitute for [[Kenedy (footballer)|Kenedy]] in a 1–0 home win over [[Trabzonspor]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]] group stage.<ref>{{cite news |title=La 'fórmula Bordalás' también funciona en Europa|trans-title=The 'Bordalás formula' also works in Europe |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/europa-league/cronica/2019/09/19/5d83c19f46163fb24a8b45b8.html |access-date=8 May 2022 |newspaper=Marca|location=Spain |date=19 September 2019 |language=es}}</ref> He played eight games of [[2019–20 UEFA Europa League|that campaign]], which ended 11 months later with a 2–0 loss on aggregate to [[Inter Milan]] in the last 16.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leveridge |first1=Sam |title=Another cruel goodbye for EuroGeta |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/inter-milan-vs-getafe/cronica/2020/08/05/5f2b1d9f22601d147d8b462a.html |access-date=8 May 2022 |newspaper=Marca|location=Spain |date=5 August 2020}}</ref>

On 3 March 2020, Getafe triggered his option to buy for €6&nbsp;million, no longer connecting him to Barcelona.<ref>[https://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/2020/03/15/5e6e786d268e3ee3758b460f.html Getafe exercise option to purchase Cucurella for six million euros] ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]''. 3 March 2020. Retrieved 27 April 2020</ref> The club fully exercised his option to buy on 30 June.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/first-team/news/1702077/getafe-exercise-option-to-purchase-marc-cucurella |title=Getafe exercise option to purchase Marc Cucurella |date=30 June 2020 |publisher=FC Barcelona |access-date=12 September 2020}}</ref>

===Brighton and Hove Albion===
[[File:Manchester United v Brighton & Hove Albion, 15 February 2022 (26).jpg|thumb|right|Cucurella playing for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in 2022]]
On 31 August 2021, Cucurella joined [[Premier League]] club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on a five-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2239897/marc-cucurella-joins-from-getafe |title=Marc Cucurella joins from Getafe |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=31 August 2021 |access-date=31 August 2021 |archive-date=31 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210831152403/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2239897/marc-cucurella-joins-from-getafe |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his debut for Brighton on 11 September, starting and playing 82 minutes before being substituted in the 1–0 away win over [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58436979 |title=Brentford 0–1 Brighton: Leandro Trossard scores last-minute winner for Seagulls |website=BBC Sport |date=11 September 2021|access-date=11 September 2021}}</ref> Eight days later, he made his home debut, playing the whole of the 2–1 victory over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58533950 |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 2–1 Leicester City: Seagulls hold off late pressure to go third |date=19 September 2021|access-date=19 September 2021 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His chipped cross set up [[Danny Welbeck]]'s headed equaliser in added time, finishing 1–1 away to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 29 December.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59751273 |title=Chelsea 1–1 Brighton & Hove Albion: Danny Welbeck heads stoppage-time equaliser for Seagulls |date=29 December 2021|access-date=29 December 2021 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 7 May 2022, he scored his first goal for the club; he netted the second of a 4–0 win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] by shooting from [[Leandro Trossard]]'s pull back.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61281254 |title=Brighton 4–0 Manchester United: Big defeat ends United's Champions League hopes |website=BBC Sport |date=7 May 2022|access-date=7 May 2022}}</ref> Three days later, at the club's end of season awards, Cucurella won Players' Player of the Season as well as being voted Player of the Season.<ref name="Awards">{{cite news |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2612228/cucurella-thanks-teammates-and-fans-for-awards |title=Cucurella thanks teammates and fans for awards |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=10 May 2022 |access-date=10 May 2022 |archive-date=18 April 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240418150300/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2612228/cucurella-thanks-teammates-and-fans-for-awards |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Chelsea===
[[File:Marc Cucurella 20042025 (1).jpg|thumb|right|Cucurella with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2025]]
On 5 August 2022, Cucurella signed for Premier League club Chelsea on a six-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cucurella becomes a Blue |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/cucurella-becomes-a-blue |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |date=5 August 2022 |access-date=5 August 2022}}</ref> The fee was reported to be worth an initial £56&nbsp;million, potentially rising to £63&nbsp;million in add-ons,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Naylor |first=Andy |date=5 August 2022 |title=Brighton and Chelsea agree Cucurella fee worth up to £63m |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3480068/2022/08/05/marc-cucurella-chelsea-brighton-transfer/ |access-date=17 July 2025 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> which was a record fee received by Brighton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2720131/marc-cucurella-makes-record-move-to-chelsea |title=Marc Cucurella makes record move to Chelsea |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=5 August 2022 |access-date=5 August 2022 |archive-date=27 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240727111719/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2720131/marc-cucurella-makes-record-move-to-chelsea |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 6 August, he made his debut as a substitute in a 1–0 away win against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chelsea opened the Premier League season with victory over Everton as Jorginho's penalty decided a scrappy contest at Goodison Park |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62358042 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=6 August 2022 |date=6 August 2022}}</ref> On 7 March 2023, he was named Player of the Match in the Champions League round-of-16-second leg match against [[Borussia Dortmund]], which ended in a 2–0 win and qualification to the quarter-final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/video/027f-177aca9f4911-ff60241c7d61-1000--player-of-the-match-marc-cucurella-highlights/ |title=Player of the Match: Marc Cucurella highlights |publisher=UEFA |date=7 March 2023 }}</ref> On 17 March 2024, he scored his first goal for the club by netting the opener in a 4–2 victory over Leicester City in the [[2023–24 FA Cup|FA Cup]] quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/video-marc-cucurella-first-chelsea-goal-as-blues-take-advantage-of-leicester-mistake-39220303 |title=(Video): Marc Cucurella first Chelsea goal as Blues take advantage of Leicester mistake |work=OneFootball |date=17 March 2024 }}</ref>

On 15 December 2024, Cucurella scored his first Premier League goal for Chelsea, a headed opener assisted by [[Noni Madueke]] in a 2–1 home victory over [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. In the same game, Cucurella would receive his first career red card, being shown a second yellow for a scuffle with Brentford's [[Kevin Schade]] after the final whistle which Schade also received a yellow card for.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c983g346n4yt |title=Chelsea beat Brentford to close in on leaders Liverpool |website=BBC Sport |date=15 December 2024 |access-date=15 December 2024}}</ref>

==International career==
After representing Spain at [[Spain national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Spain national under-17 football team|under-17]] and [[Spain national under-19 football team|under-19]] level, Cucurella was called up to the [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21 team]] in September 2019, playing [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] matches against [[Kazakhstan national under-21 football team|Kazakhstan]] and [[Montenegro national under-21 football team|Montenegro]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.sport.es/en/news/barca/riqui-puig-is-on-the-verge-of-making-his-debut-for-spains-u21-side-7594086|title= Riqui Puig is on the verge of making his debut for Spain's U21 side|website=Marca|date= 15 August 2019|location=Spain|access-date=19 June 2024}}</ref> He captained Spain to the semi-final stage of the [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2021 European U21 championship]], where they were beaten by [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.uefa.com/under21/match/2031980--spain-vs-portugal/lineups/|title=Spain 0–1 Portugal|publisher=UEFA|access-date=19 June 2024}}</ref>

Cucurella was also part of the [[Spain national under-23 football team|Spain under-23 team]] that won the silver medal at the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Olympic Games]], that took place in 2021 due to the previous year's postponement as a result of the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name=olympics>{{cite web |url=https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/en/news/brazil-beat-spain-in-extra-time-for-back-to-back-men-s-football-gold |title=Brazil beat Spain in extra-time for back-to-back men's football gold |publisher=International Olympic Committee |date=7 August 2021|access-date=23 August 2021|archive-date=23 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210823184749/https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/en/news/brazil-beat-spain-in-extra-time-for-back-to-back-men-s-football-gold|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Olympics: Tokyo 2020 chief does not rule out cancelling Games |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-57911122|access-date=24 July 2021 |website=BBC News |date=21 July 2021}}</ref>

In November 2020, manager [[Luis Enrique]] called up Cucurella to the senior [[Spain national football team|Spain]] squad for [[UEFA Nations League]] games against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and [[Germany national football team|Germany]], as [[José Gayà]] was injured.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moñino |first1=Ladislao J. |title=Luis Enrique llama a Cucurella en sustitución de Gayà|trans-title=Luis Enrique calls up Cucurella in place of Gayà |url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2020-11-12/luis-enrique-llama-a-cucurella-en-sustitucion-de-gaya.html |access-date=8 May 2022 |newspaper=El País |date=12 November 2020 |language=es}}</ref> He was an unused substitute for the fixtures.<ref>{{cite news |title=Switzerland 1–1 Spain |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54945758 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=16 November 2020}}</ref>

Due to the isolation of some national team players following the positive [[COVID-19]] test of [[Sergio Busquets]], Spain's under-21 squad were called up for the international friendly against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] on 8 June 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sefutbol.com/oficial-lista-convocados-encuentro-lituania |title=Oficial {{!}} Lista de convocados para el encuentro ante Lituania |trans-title=Official {{!}} Squad list for the match against Lithuania |publisher=Royal Spanish Football Federation |date=6 June 2021 |access-date=7 June 2021 |language=es |archive-date=8 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211008070336/https://sefutbol.com/oficial-lista-convocados-encuentro-lituania |url-status=dead }}</ref> Cucurella made his debut, acting as captain, in this match that Spain won 4–0.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/espana-vs-lituania/cronica/2021/06/08/60bfd85222601dc65d8b458f.html |title=Spain youngsters impress in Lithuania rout |newspaper=Marca|location=Spain |date=8 June 2021|access-date=8 June 2021}}</ref>

On 26 March 2024, Cucurella won his second cap for the Spain senior team, playing the full 90 minutes at left back in a 3–3 draw with [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at the [[Estadio Santiago Bernabéu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/international-friendlies/2024/live-spain-brazil_mtc1490629/live-lineup.shtml|title=Spain – Brazil|website=Eurosport|access-date=19 June 2024}}</ref>

In June 2024, Cucurella was named in Spain's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 June 2024 |title=OFFICIAL {{!}} Final Spain squad for the Euro 2024 finals |url=https://rfef.es/en/noticias/final-spain-squad-for-the-euro-2024-finals |publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] |access-date=7 June 2024 }}</ref> He made his competitive debut in the team's opening match of the tournament, starting at left back as ''La Furia Roja'' beat [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] 3–0 at Berlin's [[Olympiastadion (Berlin)|Olympiastadion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cq55l3qe24jt#Line-ups|title=Spain 3–0 Croatia LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 – score, updates & reaction|website=BBC Sport|access-date=19 June 2024}}</ref> In the [[UEFA Euro 2024 knockout stage|quarter-finals]] against Germany, Cucurella was the center of controversy after he had blocked a shot with his hand inside the penalty area, yet no penalty was awarded from the referee as his arm's movement when it hit the ball wasn't considered to be "unnaturally enlarging the body", this subsequently prevented Germany from sending the game into penalties and potentially advancing. Cucurella provided the assist on [[Mikel Oyarzabal]]'s winning goal as Spain defeated [[England national football team|England]] 2–1 in the [[UEFA Euro 2024 final|final]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tribuna.com/en/news/chelsea-2024-07-14-cucurella-assists-winning-goal-as-spain-wins-euro-2024/ |title=Cucurella assists winning goal as Spain wins Euro 2024 |publisher=Tribuna.com |date=14 July 2024 }}</ref> He was also named in the Team of the Tournament.

On 4 September 2025, during [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group E|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]], Cucurella scored his first international goal during Spain's 3–0 victory against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 September 2025 |title=Spain stroll past Bulgaria 3–0 in opening World Cup qualifier |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/football/spain-stroll-past-bulgaria-3-0-in-opening-world-cup-qualifier |access-date=4 September 2025 |website=The Straits Times}}</ref>

